{"id":"1304.7725","submitter":"Philipp Hauke","authors":"Philipp Hauke and Luca Tagliacozzo","title":"Spread of correlations in long-range interacting quantum systems","comments":"4 pages + Supplemental Material, 3+1 Figures. v2: revised\n  introduction and conclusion. Accepted in Phys. Rev. Lett","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 111, 207202 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.111.207202","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.quant-gas cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The non-equilibrium response of a quantum many-body system defines its\nfundamental transport properties and how initially localized quantum\ninformation spreads. However, for long-range-interacting quantum systems little\nis known. We address this issue by analyzing a local quantum quench in the\nlong-range Ising model in a transverse field, where interactions decay as a\nvariable power-law with distance $\\propto r^{-\\alpha}$, $\\alpha>0$. Using\ncomplementary numerical and analytical techniques, we identify three dynamical\nregimes: short-range-like with an emerging light cone for $\\alpha>2$; weakly\nlong-range for $1<\\alpha<2$ without a clear light cone but with a finite\npropagation speed of almost all excitations; and fully non-local for $\\alpha<1$\nwith instantaneous transmission of correlations. This last regime breaks\ngeneralized Lieb--Robinson bounds and thus locality. Numerical calculation of\nthe entanglement spectrum demonstrates that the usual picture of propagating\nquasi-particles remains valid, allowing an intuitive interpretation of our\nfindings via divergences of quasi-particle velocities. Our results may be\ntested in state-of-the-art trapped-ion experiments.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Apr 2013 17:54:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 16 Oct 2013 12:25:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-11-15"}
